<h1>Nurse Compact License States 2026</h1>
<p class="lead">The Nurse Licensure Compact (NLC) lets you practice in multiple states on a single license — the most important piece of paperwork for travel nurses who want maximum flexibility. Here is the current state list, how it works, and exactly how to apply.</p>

<h2>What the Compact License Is</h2>
<p>The NLC is an agreement between participating states that recognizes each other's nursing licenses. If your primary state of residence is a compact state, you automatically have a multistate license — meaning you can work in any other compact state without applying for a separate license there. You still follow each state's nursing practice act when you work there, but you do not need to apply, pay fees, or wait for approval in each state.</p>
<p>For travel nurses, this is transformative. Without a compact license, taking an assignment in a new state means 6-12 weeks of licensing paperwork, endorsement fees of $50-$200, and delays that can cost you contracts. With a compact license, you can accept contracts in most of the country within days.</p>

