<h2>How to Get a Compact License</h2>
<p>You do not apply for a "compact license" separately — your existing license becomes multistate automatically if your primary state of residence is a compact state. Here is how it works:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Your home state must be a compact state.</strong> The compact is based on where you live, not where you currently hold a license. If you live in Texas and have an active Texas license, you have a multistate license.</li>
<li><strong>You must maintain your primary residence in a compact state.</strong> If you move to California (non-compact), your multistate privilege ends and you need only a California license.</li>
<li><strong>Your home state license must be active and in good standing.</strong> Expired, inactive, or disciplined licenses lose multistate privileges.</li>
<li><strong>You can practice in any compact state</strong> under your home state license, following that state's practice laws.</li>
</ol>

<h2>If You Currently Live in a Non-Compact State</h2>
<p>This is the most common question from nurses who want to travel. If you live in California, New York, or another non-compact state, you cannot get a compact license until you change your primary state of residence to a compact state. Some travel nurses strategically establish residency in a compact state — typically Texas, Florida, or a nearby compact state — to gain multistate privileges.</p>

<table>
<tr><th>Situation</th><th>What to Do</th></tr>
<tr><td>Live in compact state, have compact license</td><td>You're set — practice in any compact state immediately</td></tr>
<tr><td>Live in non-compact state, want to travel</td><td>Apply for individual endorsements in each target state; or establish residency in a compact state</td></tr>
<tr><td>Currently hold license in compact state but live elsewhere</td><td>Your compact privilege may not apply — compact is based on residence, not license location</td></tr>
<tr><td>Moving to a new compact state for travel</td><td>Your home state license retains multistate privileges — no new application needed</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Endorsement: How to Get Licensed in Non-Compact States</h2>
<p>When you need to work in a non-compact state (or need primary licensure there), you apply for endorsement — transferring your active RN license to that state. General process:</p>
<ol>
<li>Verify you meet the new state's requirements (some states require additional coursework, live hours, or exams)</li>
<li>Submit application to the new state's board of nursing with the endorsement fee ($50-$200)</li>
<li>Request NURSYS verification from your home state (most states use NURSYS for electronic verification)</li>
<li>Wait for processing — ranges from 2 weeks (Texas) to 6 months (California)</li>
<li>Some states issue temporary practice permits that allow you to work while the full license processes</li>
</ol>

<h2>NURSYS: The Endorsement Shortcut</h2>
<p>NURSYS is the online nurse license verification system operated by NCSBN. Most compact and many non-compact states participate. When you apply for endorsement, submitting through NURSYS can reduce processing time significantly because verification is electronic rather than paper-based. Check nursys.com to see if your home state and target state both participate before starting your endorsement.</p>

